WEBVTT

00:00:02.480 --> 00:00:06.900
So the other reaction I want to show you is the anti-Marcovnikov hydrohallogenation.

00:00:07.219 --> 00:00:11.599
So remember when we were looking at addition reactions, we were looking at hydrohallogenation

00:00:11.599 --> 00:00:16.140
and we were understanding that that was a regio-specific reaction.

00:00:16.780 --> 00:00:22.500
Regio-specific meaning that the halogen would always go to the more substituted of the

00:00:22.500 --> 00:00:28.160
two carbons participating in the pi bond because of the fact that it would only go by the

00:00:28.160 --> 00:00:31.059
more stable carbocation intermediate.

00:00:31.199 --> 00:00:34.979
Remember this pi bond would get the proton, leave the secondary carbocation and then

00:00:34.979 --> 00:00:41.159
that's where the bromide would go and we'd get the Marcovnikov product in a regio-specific

00:00:41.159 --> 00:00:41.679
manner.

00:00:42.039 --> 00:00:46.439
But then we didn't look at the mechanism but we also noted the fact that in the presence

00:00:46.439 --> 00:00:52.759
of peroxides this would shift to anti-Marcovnikov regio-specificity.

00:00:52.759 --> 00:00:59.100
In other words we would get the halogen on the less substituted of the two carbons participating

00:00:59.100 --> 00:00:59.899
in the pi bond.

00:01:00.259 --> 00:01:06.239
And we didn't look at why, well here's why, it's a free radical reaction and so the peroxides

00:01:06.239 --> 00:01:08.359
obviously play a very key role in this.

00:01:08.700 --> 00:01:09.379
So let's take a look.

00:01:09.819 --> 00:01:14.840
The initiation step is going to be provided by the peroxides and so remember when we talked

00:01:14.840 --> 00:01:21.519
about oxygen, oxygen, covalent bonds as ones that are able to undergo homolytic bond

00:01:21.519 --> 00:01:22.000
cleavage.

00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:23.579
That's the initiation step.

00:01:23.920 --> 00:01:28.739
So we have this oxygen oxygen covalent bond undergoing homolysis and then we get two

00:01:28.739 --> 00:01:30.659
hydroxyl radicals.

00:01:30.939 --> 00:01:34.900
So it's those hydroxyl radicals that are going to propagate the formation above other

00:01:34.900 --> 00:01:35.400
radicals.

00:01:35.519 --> 00:01:40.219
So let's say that a hydroxyl radical finds one of these molecules of HBR.

00:01:40.599 --> 00:01:45.480
Well what's going to happen is this radical and then one electron from this covalent bond

00:01:45.480 --> 00:01:49.680
are going to form a new one and now we've got a water molecule and then that's going

00:01:49.680 --> 00:01:52.859
to propagate the existence of a bromine radical.

00:01:53.519 --> 00:01:59.140
Then from there this is the key step because this is where the regio specificity is involved.

00:01:59.700 --> 00:02:04.519
The bromine radical is going to interact with this pi bond that is necessary for the

00:02:04.519 --> 00:02:08.620
addition reaction and what's going to happen is it's going to form a new carbon bromine

00:02:08.620 --> 00:02:14.560
bond but it is going to do it in regio specific manner because of the stability of the alkyo

00:02:14.560 --> 00:02:15.740
radical that it will generate.

00:02:15.740 --> 00:02:21.400
So in other words one of these pi electrons is going to go to form a covalent bond with

00:02:21.400 --> 00:02:27.139
this bromine radical and it is only going to happen here because if it does so then the

00:02:27.139 --> 00:02:33.419
other pi electron will go to this carbon, the secondary carbon leaving the more stable

00:02:33.419 --> 00:02:36.120
of the two possible alkyo radical intermediates.

00:02:36.300 --> 00:02:41.980
If the bromine radical interacted at this position and this pi electron went to form the

00:02:42.120 --> 00:02:46.219
new carbon bromine bond there then that would mean that the other pi electron would be

00:02:46.219 --> 00:02:52.659
left on the primary carbon and we then have a primary alkyo radical intermediate and

00:02:52.659 --> 00:02:55.960
that is the less stable of the two so it will not produce that.

00:02:56.360 --> 00:03:02.300
So in a regio specific manner the bromine will add to the less substituted of the two

00:03:02.300 --> 00:03:04.219
carbons participating in the pi bond.

00:03:04.639 --> 00:03:10.840
That leaves an alkyo radical intermediate which will then go ahead and undergo another

00:03:10.840 --> 00:03:16.580
step with HBR and it will just extract a proton there leaving another bromine radical

00:03:16.580 --> 00:03:16.819
there.

00:03:17.000 --> 00:03:21.340
Recall once again that these are all single headed electron pushing arrows denoting

00:03:21.340 --> 00:03:26.400
the movement of a singular electron and so we have gotten to our product here.

00:03:27.400 --> 00:03:35.879
This is our anti-marcovnicoff hydro halogenation product regio specific to be the less substituted

00:03:35.879 --> 00:03:40.460
alkyo bromide of the two possibilities and we have managed to do it all with propagation

00:03:40.460 --> 00:03:44.180
steps there could be termination steps choose anything.

00:03:45.180 --> 00:03:50.699
This radical bromine radical hydroxyl radical anything if two radical species meet they'll

00:03:50.699 --> 00:03:55.219
terminate but none of them were needed in the mechanism generating the products so we didn't

00:03:55.219 --> 00:03:55.639
draw them.

00:03:56.099 --> 00:04:02.340
So once again hydroxyl radical initiates propagates the existence of the bromine radical and

00:04:02.340 --> 00:04:09.580
then the bromine radical goes ahead and adds in regio specific manner specifically in an

00:04:09.580 --> 00:04:15.780
anti-marcovnicoff manner so that it generates the more stable of the possible alkyo radical

00:04:15.780 --> 00:04:16.600
intermediates.

00:04:17.160 --> 00:04:22.439
So that will shed some light on the mystery we understood the mechanism before for the

00:04:22.439 --> 00:04:28.860
Marcovnicoff hydro halogenation and now we know the mechanism for the anti-marcovnicoff

00:04:28.860 --> 00:04:29.939
variety as well.

